items.title: Squinting Squid
items.caption: Your Shot photographer Luiz Felipe Puntel captured a close encounter with a curious squid attracted by the dive light. Cephalapods—like squid, octopuses, and cuttlefish—are among the most intelligent invertebrates, often able to solve simple puzzles in addition to their dazzling camouflage skills.
items.altText: Picture of a squid in black and white

social.og:title: Squid Close-Up Image  | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: A squid swims in for a night dive close-up in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Colorful Close-Up
items.caption: A pet chameleon's close-up reveals the bright colors of its scaly skin. The common assumption that chameleons change color to blend into their surroundings isn't the whole story: The reptiles' showy skin also communicates information to its potential enemies or mates.
items.altText: Picture of chameleon's colorful skin close-up

social.og:title: Colorful Chameleon Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: A colorful chameleon preens for a close-up in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Seeking Refuge
items.caption: On the border of Myanmar and Bangladesh, refugee familes take shelter inside large concrete pipes. They are members of the Rohingya, a people group in Myanmar that suffer extreme persecution. As of May 2018, almost a million Rohingya have fled Myanma to seek shelter in Bangladesh.
items.altText: Picture of Rohingya families taking shelter in large concrete pipes in Bangladesh after fleeing Myanmar

social.og:title: Rohingya Refugees Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: Rohingya refugee families take shelter in large concrete pipes in Bangladesh after fleeing persecution in Myanmar in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Windmills in the Mist
items.caption: Windmills peek out from the fog in Zaandam, Netherlands. "I have been dreaming of these conditions for years and I finally got them!" says Your Shot photographer Albert Dros. "Being able to capture it with these conditions was magical."
items.altText: Picture of windmills in fog in Zaandam, Netherlands

social.og:title: Dutch Windmills Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: Windmills peek through the fog in Zaandam, Netherlands, in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Crazy Kids
items.caption: "A rambunctious group of American mountain goat kids practice leaping from one rock prominence to another atop the jagged stone of a 14,000-foot tall mountain," explains Your Shot photographer Tony Oswald of this scene in Freeland, Colorado. "Testing their maneuvering skills through such play will help them live and thrive at this altitude as they become adults."
items.altText: Picture of three mountain goat kids scrambling atop a jagged mountain in Colorado

social.og:title: Mountain Goat Kids Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: Mountain Goat kids scramble atop a mountain in Freeland, Colorado, in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Inside the Pink Mosque
items.caption: Rahman Soleymani is part of a team carefully restoring the tiles in the winter prayer hall of the Nasir-ol-molk Mosque, also known as the Pink Mosque, in Shiraz, Iran. "I love the vivid colors of the stained glass illuminated by warm sunlight and the delicate floral patterns of the tiling," says Your Shot photographer Athikhom Saengchai. "It is definitely one of the most beautiful places in Iran."
items.altText: Picture of a man restoring titles in the Pink Mosque in Shiraz, Iran

social.og:title: Mosque Restoration Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: A man carefully works to restore tiles inside Iran's Pink Mosque in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Mating Ritual
items.caption: A pair of rat snakes seem to dance as they engage in a mating ritual in Lonāvale, India. As their name implies, they feed primarily on rodents, and they present no threat to humans.
items.altText: Picture of two rat snakes mating in tall grass in India

social.og:title: Mating Ritual Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: Rat snakes appear to dance as they engage in a mating ritual in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Vanishing Bridge
items.caption: Two San Francisco icons merge in this photo: the Golden Gate Bridge, and fog. The highest points of the bridge measure 746 feet tall—nearly 69 stories.
items.altText: Picture of fog covering the top of the Golden Gate Bridge in San Francisco, California

social.og:title: Golden Fog Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: Fog covers the top of the Golden Gate Bridge in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Can You Believe?
items.caption: Your Shot photographer Gregory Piper met these moray eels off the coast of Myanmar. "The curiosity and behavior of Moray Eels never stops amazing me," he says. "In this shot these two curious eels almost seemed to be checking me out and talking amongst themselves about the curious diver in front of them."
items.altText: Picture of two moray eels underwater off the coast of Myanmar

social.og:title: Moray Eels Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: Two moray eels take in the presence of an underwater photographer off the coast of Myanmar in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Head in the Sand
items.caption: Two men engage in a bout of Schwingen, or Swiss wrestling. The traditional sport goes back centuries. In each bout, the opponents try to grab each others Schwingerhosen, or wrestling breeches, and throw each other on the ground. The first person whose shoulders touch the ground loses.
items.altText: Picture of two men participating in traditional Switzerland wrestling

social.og:title: Swiss Wrestling Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: Two men engage in a bout of Schwinger, or Swiss wrestling, in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Sunset in Paradise
items.caption: A lone mangrove stands in the waters of Bunaken Island, Indonesia. In the background is the volcanic island of Manado Tua.
items.altText: Picture of the silhouettes of a mangrove tree and a person standing in the waters of Bunaken Island, Indonesia, as the sun sets behind them

social.og:title: Indonesian Sunset Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: The sun sets behind a mangrove tree in the waters of Bunaken Island, Indonesia, in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Sea Dragon
items.caption: Off the coast of Flinders, Australia, swims a male weedy sea dragon. Like its relative the seahorse, the male sea dragon will care for the eggs laid on his tail by his female mate.
items.altText: Picture of a male weedy sea dragon carrying eggs on his tail while swimming off the coast of Australia

social.og:title: Weedy Sea Dragon Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: A male weedy sea dragon with a tail full of fertilized eggs swims off the coast of Australia in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: In Full Feather
items.caption: A blue-and-gold macaw preens its feathers at the Wildlife Learning Center in Sylmar, California. The birds, when properly cared for, can live for more than sixty years.
items.altText: Picture of a blue-and-gold macaw preening its feathers at the Wildlife Learning Center in Sylmar, California

social.og:title: Magnificent Macaw Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: A blue-and-gold macaw preens its feathers at the Wildlife Learning Center in Sylmar, California, in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Full Bloom
items.caption: A farmer harvests tulips in the Netherlands. Last year, the nation produced an estimated 2 billion bulbs.
items.altText: Picture of a piece of machinery harvesting a row of tulips in a colorful field in the Netherlands

social.og:title: Flower Farming Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: A farmer harvests tulips in the Netherlands in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Sandy Sunscreen
items.caption: A male elephant seal flips sand up onto his back while resting at California's Point Reyes National Seashore. Sand acts as a sunscreen, keeping the seals cool while napping on land.
items.altText: Picture of a male elephant seal flipping sand onto his back while he lies on a beach in California

social.og:title: Sand Bath Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: An elephant seal gives himself a layer of sunscreen by flipping sand onto his back on a beach in California in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Colorful War
items.caption: Your Shot photographer Alireza Akbari took this photo of a Holi celebration in Mathura, India. "It was the beginning of a colorful war, and each person was a lone ranger who was carrying a bag full of colorful powder," he remembers. "They were throwing that powder to bless each other as a welcoming celebration to spring."
items.altText: Picture of people throwing colored powder as a celebration of Holi in India

social.og:title: Holi Celebration Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: People throw colored powders to celebrate Holi in Mathura, India, in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Oak Alley
items.caption: Twenty-eight live oak trees line the path to Oak Alley Plantation in Vacherie, Louisiana. Built as a sugarcane plantation in the early 19th century, Oak Alley is now open to the public as a National Historic Landmark.
items.altText: Picture of oak trees covering a path toward a large, white plantation home

social.og:title: Oak Alley Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: Twenty-eight live oak trees line the path to Oak Alley Plantation in Vacherie, Louisiana, in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Sea Bound
items.caption: Every year, millions of tiny, baby olive ridley sea turtles hatch on Rushikulya Beach in India. It's a treacherous journey—experts estimate that only 1 in every 1,000 baby sea turtles will make it to the water before being killed by a predator.
items.altText: Picture of dozens of baby sea turtles crawling across the beach to the ocean

social.og:title: Baby Sea Turtles Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: On India's Rushikhulya Beach, dozens of baby sea turtles attempt to make it into the ocean in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Neck and Neck
items.caption: Two young male giraffes take a break from fighting in Tanzania's Ngorongoro Conservation Area. Giraffes fight by bashing their necks against each other, trying to establish dominance and a reputation as the better mate.
items.altText: Picture of two male giraffes standing facing away from each other after a bout of necking in Tanzania

social.og:title: Resting Giraffes Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: Two male giraffes take a break from necking, or fighting, in Tanzania in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Prairie Storm
items.caption: An enormous storm cloud swirls towards the ground in western Nebraska. Your Shot photographer Sean Ramsey took this picture with a 16mm lens, meaning he was incredibly close to this ominous cloud.
items.altText: Picture of an enormous storm cloud spiraling toward the ground in Nebraska

social.og:title: Prairie Twister Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: A storm cloud spirals towards the ground in western Nebraska in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: In the Stretch
items.caption: "Photographing the octopus truly is an art and it is a skill that has taken me years to develop," says Your Shot photographer Ian Nelson, who took this shot off the coast of Maui, Hawaii. "Their camouflage is so effective that they can blend the color and texture of their skin with their surroundings. Once you have found an octopus, the fun begins. With some patience and a bit of luck, hopefully, you can witness them hunting, traveling, mating, or simply hiding in a hole."
items.altText: Picture of an octopus underwater, reaching up with one of its tentacles

social.og:title: Octopus Stretch Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: An octopus stretches one of its tentacles in the waters off the coast of Maui, Hawaii, in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Citadel Sunset
items.caption: The sun sets behind the Temple of Hercules on the Amman Citadel in Jordan. An inscription on the marble indicates that the temple was constructed in the year 162 AD.
items.altText: Picture of a sunset behind the ruins of the Temple of Hercules in Amman, Jordan

social.og:title: Citadel Sunset Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: The sun sets behind the ruins of the Temple of Hercules in Amman, Jordan, in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Muscle Beach
items.caption: A weightlifting enthusiast works out at Muscle Beach, an outdoor gym in Venice, California. The gym has long been a hotspot for famous bodybuilders, including Arnold Schwarzenegger.
items.altText: Picture of a weightlifter picking up weights at Muscle Beach, California

social.og:title: Muscle Beach Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: A weightlifter gets in a workout at Muscle Beach in Venice, California, in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Pony Up
items.caption: A highland pony gallops across snowy fields in the rural highlands of Scotland. Highland ponies are native to Scotland, their thick coats helping them withstand the harsh winters.
items.altText: Picture of a highland pony galloping across a snowy field in Scotland

social.og:title: Snowy Pony Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: A highland pony gallops across a snowy field in Scotland in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Hazy Day
items.caption: "The sea was very rough and the undertow was very strong," says Your Shot photographer Sandra Cattaneo Adorno of this day on Ipanema Beach in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. "The bathers were hesitating to get into the sea. A thick mist hung over the beach and was coloured by the light of the sunset."
items.altText: Picture of people surrounded by a yellow mist while on Ipanema Beach in Brazil

social.og:title: Misty Beach Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: Visitors to Ipanema Beach, Brazil, are surrounded by mist in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Quiet Forest
items.caption: A thick forest of cedar trees stands tall on Terceira Island, in the Portuguese archipelago of the Azores. You wouldn't know it by looking at this peaceful picture, but Terceira Island is home to the biggest city of the Azores, Angra do Heroísmo, which was founded in the 15th century.
items.altText: Picture of a dirt path going through a cedar forest in the Azores Islands

social.og:title: Portuguese Forest Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: A quiet cedar forest stands on Terceira Island, Portugal, in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Night Lights
items.caption: People enjoy a night out on the town in Tokyo. Taking this photo meant taking a risk, as Your Shot photographer Alan Wong had to set his camera on a tripod in the midst of late-night revelers. "There were quite a few people who were drunk and attempted to push my camera," he recounts, "but it was definitely a shot to remember."
items.altText: Picture of the silhouettes of people against the large neon signs in Tokyo

social.og:title: Tokyo Lights Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: Light-night revelers in Tokyo are silhouetted against enormous neon signs in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Rainbow Road
items.caption: When owned by slaveholders, the buildings of Cape Town's Bo-Kaap neighborhood were all painted white. Upon gaining their freedom, the quarter's majority-Muslim occupants painted their houses in bright colors to celebrate Eid, the end of Ramadan.
items.altText: Picture of colorful buildings in Cape Town

social.og:title: Colorful Cape Town Street | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: Brightly painted houses line a Cape Town street in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: Mother and Calf
items.caption: A humpback whale supports her very young calf near the ocean's surface. Though smaller than blue whales, humpback calves are born already about 10 feet long and weighing up to a ton.
items.altText: Picture of a humpback whale calf and mother

social.og:title: Humpback Whale Calf Image | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: A humpback whale supports her young calf in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.

items.title: A Wise Man
items.caption: A Shipibo man named Senencina overlooks a river in the Peruvian Amazon. The Shipibo-Conibo tribe includes about 20,000 people in Peru, Brazil, and Bolivia.
items.altText: Picture of Senencina, a Peruvian Shipibo wise man

social.og:title: Indigenous Peruvian Portrait | National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day
social.og:description: An indigenous Peruvian overlooks an Amazonian river in this National Geographic Your Shot Photo of the Day.
